T1  - Relationships of Personality to Perceptual and Behavioral Responses in Stimulating and Nonstimulating Tasks
AU  - Kim, Jay S.
Y1  - 1980/06/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255433
DO  - 10.5465/255433
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 307
EP  - 319
VL  - 23
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study tested the interaction effects of task stimulation and extroversion on worker satisfaction and performance. In addition, the role of extroversion and neuroticism dimensions of personality on expectancy and task perceptions of workers was investigated. Among other findings, the task-extraversion interaction hypothesis was confirmed for worker satisfaction, but not for performance.
AB  - This study tested the interaction effects of task stimulation and extroversion on worker satisfaction and performance. In addition, the role of extroversion and neuroticism dimensions of personality on expectancy and task perceptions of workers was investigated. Among other findings, the task-extraversion interaction hypothesis was confirmed for worker satisfaction, but not for performance.
